BONANZA CREEK LTER

Juvenile Snowshoe Hares

Jake Nyiri

Introduction

This exploratory analysis examines some of the data collected at multiple Bonanza Creek Experimental Forest Long-Term Ecological Research sites in Alaska from 1998-2010. This is a large-scale ecological and climate research center located in boreal forest and tundra around the city of Fairbanks. Relationships between sex and weight of juvenile snowshoe hares in the area are examined, as well as any potential relationship between weight and limb length.

Data and Methods

Counts and measurements of juvenile snowshoes hares were collected from trapping regimes at three sites in the LTER over 12 years (Kielland, K., F.S. Chapin, R.W. Ruess, and Bonanza Creek LTER. 2017. Snowshoe hare physical data in Bonanza Creek Experimental Forest: 1999-Present ver 22. Environmental Data Initiative.). Hare weight, sex, foot length, and ear length were recorded. In this analysis, weights were compared across the three sites and summary statistics prepared for both sexes of hare. A two-sample t-test was used to explore differences between the average weights of male and female hares, with a Cohens d effect size determined. Relationships between hare weight and hind foot length were examined and a linear model created to try to describe the relationship. All analysis was conducted with R 3.6.2


Figure 1
Juvenile Snowshoe Hare Counts (1998-2010)

The counts appear to decrease over the timespan of the study, from a maximum of 126 to a minimum of 2. However, for two years (2002 and 2009) there were no identifiable juveniles counted, and the majority of the ages are listed as NA. If we treat those years as 0 juveniles counted then the average yearly count is 27 with a median of 15.5. If we do not include those years at all, the average count is 31.5 with a median of 18.5. The large number of NA ages in these years indicates that a more regimented sampling and identification system amy be in order.



Figure 2
Juvenile Snowshoe Hare Weights By Sex and Location

The data indicates that average female weights are similar in the upland and riparian areas (808kg and 824kg respectively) and somewhat higher in the lowland (1022kg). The average male weight varied less by location(1073kg for lowland, 950kg for upland and 929kg for riparian).
